<quantity box="[577,636,1928,1954]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" unit="km" value="4.0">4 km</quantity>
S of Trapezonti; Agios Nikolaos (Taygetos); Arna (Taygetos); Gorani, Moni Golas; Gythion; Gythion, beach East; Mavrovouni (Gythion, Stomio Bay); Mystras; Chania; near Dafni; Paleopanagia (Taygetos); Loggastra; Karvelas; Kosiarion; Monemvasia;
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,152,323]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,152,179]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Characters of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[480,615,154,179]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anemoninus">
<emphasis box="[480,615,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">anemoninus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group described above, plus the following characters. Male with lateral setation of abdomen and setation of elytra black. Head and pronotum usually with dark and unsaturated hues of violet or green. Paramera similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[685,820,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anemoninus">
<emphasis box="[685,820,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">anemoninus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and not diagnostic, everted endophallus similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[182,317,262,287]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anemoninus">
<emphasis box="[182,317,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">anemoninus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but diagnostic (
<figureCitation box="[500,639,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–31" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1869,1894]" captionTargetBox="[163,1408,194,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 25–31. Pygopleurus pseudopsilotrichius (Petrovitz, 1958), habitus and genitalia. 25, male (Lakonia, Gorani); 26, male (Arcadia, Karitena); 27, female (Lakonia, Chanià); 28, female (Lakonia, Gorani); 29, left paramere in lateral and dorsal view (Laconia, Chanià); 30, everted endophallus in left lateral view (Laconia, Chanià); 31, left genital sclerites of female (Laconia, Dafni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458852" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458852/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Figs. 29–30</figureCitation>
). Female similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[944,1107,262,287]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anemoninus">
<emphasis box="[944,1107,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">P. anemoninus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, reliably identifiable only by association with males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[151,1316,368,396]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1316,368,396]" box="[151,1316,368,396]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,411,368,395]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[312,398,368,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1266,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1408,181,1235]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[170,1416,181,1241]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 32. Pygopleurus anemoninus (Brullé, 1832) and P. pseudopsilotrichius (Petrovitz, 1958): geographical, altitudinal, and temporal distribution of records. Red curves showing the expected distribution if the species was uniformly present at all heights and all times (see Material and methods)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458854/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Restricted to Central and Southern 
<collectingRegion box="[812,954,369,395]" country="Greece" name="Peloponnisos" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Peloponnese</collectingRegion>
(Lakonia, Arcadia and Argolis).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,440,647]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,516,440,467]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
Eco-ethological notes (
<figureCitation box="[418,503,440,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1266,1291]" captionTargetBox="[170,1408,181,1235]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[170,1416,181,1241]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 32. Pygopleurus anemoninus (Brullé, 1832) and P. pseudopsilotrichius (Petrovitz, 1958): geographical, altitudinal, and temporal distribution of records. Red curves showing the expected distribution if the species was uniformly present at all heights and all times (see Material and methods)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458854/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
The adults of this species are active between the middle of April (
<date box="[1252,1360,440,467]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
12 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1281,1294,440,454]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">th</superScript>
April
</date>
, Laconia, Monemvasia, sea level) and the end of May (
<date box="[702,802,476,503]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
27 
<superScript attach="left" box="[731,744,476,490]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">th</superScript>
May
</date>
, Arcadia, Vytina, altitude not recorded, but close to 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
). The species, which is usually abundant, is found from sea level up to 
<quantity box="[959,1045,513,539]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
, both elevations being documented in the mountain ranges of Parnon and Taygetos. Like its vicariant species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[1013,1176,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anemoninus">
<emphasis box="[1013,1176,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">P. anemoninus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the adults are mainly found feeding or mating on 
<taxonomicName box="[465,560,586,611]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Papaver" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[465,560,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Papaver</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[575,739,585,611]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cistaceae" genus="Cistus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanus">
<emphasis box="[575,739,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Cistus incanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and Asteracee (white or yellow Tubuliflorae and Liguliflorae like 
<taxonomicName box="[200,274,621,647]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Cymuloporidae" genus="Crepis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[200,274,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Crepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[328,432,621,647]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Anthemis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[328,432,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Anthemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,692,899]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,400,692,719]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Petrovitz" baseAuthorityYear="1958" box="[410,780,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudopsilotrichius">
<emphasis box="[410,780,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Pygopleurus pseudopsilotrichius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described as a distinct species, but placed into synonymy with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[292,455,730,755]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anemoninus">
<emphasis box="[292,455,730,755]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">P. anemoninus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Baraud, J." box="[497,662,729,755]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" pagination="331 - 375" refId="ref29740" refString="Baraud, J. (1989) Revision du genre Pygopleurus Motschulsky (Coleoptera, Scarabaoidea: Glaphyridae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 25 (3), 331 - 375, 89 figs." type="book chapter" year="1989">Baraud (1989)</bibRefCitation>
. Comparing more than 
<specimenCount box="[926,1091,729,755]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="generic">720 specimens</specimenCount>
of both nominal taxa, we have ascertained that examined populations can be consistently distinguished by the characters mentioned in the diagnosis. In addition, populations distinguished on morphological basis are distributed on two parapatric ranges (fig. 32). In spite of the rather limited morphological differences encountered, the mentioned observations and the absence of intermediate populations support treating these as distinct species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
